title: Show HN: Starface.club – Show the World
text:
Hi Hackernews! Show off to the world whatever you want to show off. An ad for your new startup, a photo of your favorite pet, or a lovely message to the world. Whatever you think is best.

The content rotates full-screen in the background, can link to an external website, and impression information is available to every visitor.

Ask HN: Explosion of “Amazon Account has been locked” scam texts?
text:
I know scam emails/texts aren’t new, by far. But over the past few months, my whole family has been hit with an explosion of scam messages claiming our Amazon account has been locked (with, of course, a phishing link to get passwords).

Generally curious if this is more widespread vs. previous scams, as this seems worse than anything I’ve seen before.

I really wish iOS would do better at filtering these, or allowing custom filters/blocking to help. Of course, a recent iOS update added a quicker way to report+block, but unfortunately isn’t slowing these scammers down.

Mostly a rant + genuinely curious if this really is worse and more widespread than even what is usual.

Would you consider pay half now and then for each year a device lasts?
text:
Over the past 5 years we can notice aggressive planned obsolescence applied across pretty much all products. From an all-sealed non-repairable designs to software limitations it's visible even to the non-technical users.

We can differentiate two product cycles. Premium products with no planned obsolescence - higher price, less frequent change of device. Mainstream products - designed to be replaced frequently, lower price.

Ideas

Initial price as low as mainstream. Users pay a fixed additional fee for each functioning year of the product thus reaching premium price if the product lasts longer.

A marketplace where only products with no planned obsolescence are sold based on the above model

Would you switch to such a purchasing model as a user?

Would you switch to such a production model as a company?
